{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2245ea6b-42dc-454a-9162-55fbdd41d61f","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## 1. Deeply Nested Imports (3 levels)\n`EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`\n\nEach import requires MSBuild to resolve the path, open the file, and parse XML. Chained imports add latency linearly and are harder to cache.\n\n## 2. Expensive File I/O via Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` during **evaluation** is costly—it performs synchronous disk I/O on every evaluation pass (design-time builds, restore, IDE refresh, etc.), not just at build time.\n\n## 3. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe recursive wildcard `**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to enumerate the entire directory tree during evaluation. In large repos this is extremely slow and defeats glob caching.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Flatten or consolidate the `.props` chain into a single import.\n- Replace `ReadAllText` with a target that runs at build time (not evaluation), or remove it entirely.\n- Narrow the `AdditionalFiles` glob to specific file extensions/directories actually needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b84ba16c-9e82-46ed-b2ca-93091b880716","outputTokens":362,"requestId":"F01B:149EED:285F01F:2C9DD21:69F9452D"},"id":"918dd0e8-fc1a-419b-ab8b-17b06b68dd35","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:17:41.649Z","parentId":"b7b733f0-01e7-495c-9224-a51bf0295cc9"}
